MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 1979720859}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: f4688fdb7df04437aeb418b961361dc5, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  m_Material: {fileID: 0}
  m_Color: {r: 1, g: 1, b: 1, a: 1}
  m_RaycastTarget: 1
  m_RaycastPadding: {x: 0, y: 0, z: 0, w: 0}
  m_Maskable: 1
  m_OnCullStateChanged:
    m_PersistentCalls:
      m_Calls: []
  m_text: ">>>  Manual Phishing Detection - Module #1  <<<\n\nIn this guide, I want
    to introduce how you can analyze a phishing email by looking for signs that it
    is suspicious and requires further investigation. We\u2019ll use a multi-faceted
    approach that examines the email\u2019s content, technical headers, embedded
    links, and any accompanying attachments.\n\nEach of these components offers unique
    clues that, when combined, can reveal the sender\u2019s true intent and potentially
    prevent a serious security incident.\n\nA phishing email is typically made up
    of four key components: the headers, the content, links in that content, and
    any attachments. We\u2019ll want to analyze each of these components in turn
    to determine whether the email is malicious and whether there is any useful information
    we can extract from it.\n\n*** Email Headers ***\n\nLet\u2019s begin with the
    header. The email header contains technical information about the message\u2019s
    origin and the servers it passed through on its journey across the internet.
    This information can provide crucial evidence when identifying a phishing email.
    Within headers, you should examine:\n\n - The From Address  \n - The Reply-To
    Address  \n - The Received Headers  \n\nFirst, check the From Address. Does it
    appear legitimate? Compare the display name (for example, \u201CJohn Smith \u2013
    IT Support\u201D) with the actual email address.\n\nAttackers often use a display
    name that looks trustworthy, such as a company representative or well-known brand,
    while the underlying email address comes from an unrelated or suspicious domain.\n\nA
    mismatch between the display name and the actual sender address is a red flag.
    Next, review the Reply-To Address. Sometimes phishing emails use a legitimate-looking
    From address but specify a completely different Reply-To address.\n\nIf the reply
    address points to an unrelated or unusual domain, that is suspicious. In some
    cases, there may be no Reply-To address at all, which can also be unusual depending
    on context.\n\nThen examine the Received Headers and authentication results.
    If applicable, look at whether checks with email verification tools like SPF,
    DKIM, and DMARC pass or fail.\n\nA failed or misaligned authentication result
    does not automatically prove an email is malicious, but it does increase suspicion,
    especially if the message claims to come from a well-known organization that
    normally has properly configured email authentication.\n\n*** Email Content ***\n\nNext,
    analyze the body of the email. This is often the most obvious place to detect
    phishing attempts. Common warning signs include:\n\n - Urgent or threatening
    language  \n\nMessages that claim your account will be suspended immediately,
    that legal action will be taken, or that you must act within minutes are designed
    to create panic and bypass rational thinking.  \n\n - Generic greetings  \n\nPhrases
    like \u201CDear Customer\u201D or \u201CDear User\u201D instead of your actual
    name can indicate a mass phishing campaign.  \n\n - Poor grammar and spelling
    mistakes  \n\nWhile modern phishing emails are increasingly polished, sometimes
    even generated with AI, obvious language issues can still be a red flag.  \n\n-
    Unusual requests or offers  \n\nFor example: An executive asking you to urgently
    transfer funds or purchase gift cards. A vendor you have never worked with asking
    you to review an invoice. A request to reset your password when you did not initiate
    one. \n\n- An offer or opportunity which seems too good to be true. \n \nIf a
    request seems out of character or unexpected, pause and verify it through an
    independent communication channel. \n \n - Inconsistent branding  \n\nIf an email
    claims to be from a well-known service, compare its logos, formatting, tone,
    and overall design with legitimate emails from that organization. Poor-quality
    graphics, slightly altered logos, unusual color schemes, or inconsistent formatting
    can indicate impersonation.  \nFor example, an email might claim to be from a
    digital document-signing service and ask you to review a document. While the
    language may be professional and free of grammatical errors, the branding could
    look slightly off. Some indicators are low-resolution logos, unusual layout,
    or styling that doesn\u2019t match the official website. Even without threatening
    language, this inconsistency can signal a phishing attempt.  \n\n*** Link Analysis
    ***\n\nPhishing emails frequently contain malicious links. This is one of the
    primary attack methods, as attackers aim to redirect victims to credential-harvesting
    pages or malware-hosting infrastructure. When analyzing links, look for:\n\n-
    URL deception  \n\nThe visible text may say one thing (e.g., a trusted company
    name), but the actual hyperlink points to a completely different domain.  \n\n-
    Misspelled or look-alike domains  \n\nFor example, substituting letters with
    similar-looking characters or adding extra words to make the domain appear legitimate
    at first glance.  \n\n - URL shorteners used to obscure the true destination
    of a link.  \n - Insecure connections  \n\nToday, legitimate services almost
    always use HTTPS. If a link directs to an HTTP site, especially one requesting
    sensitive information, that is highly suspicious.  \n\nIf you choose to investigate
    a link, avoid clicking it directly from your primary device. Instead, use a secure
    analysis environment or a link-inspection tool to observe where it redirects
    and what network requests are made. Sometimes the first page may appear benign,
    but further redirects may lead to suspicious infrastructure.\n\n*** Attachments
    ***\n\nThe final component to analyze is any attachment. Although modern security
    solutions have reduced the prevalence of malicious attachments in some environments,
    they are still widely used in phishing campaigns. Be cautious of:\n\n - Unexpected
    attachments, especially if you were not anticipating a document, invoice, or
    file.  \n - Dangerous file types, such as executable files (.exe), script files
    (e.g., .ps1), or macro-enabled documents.  \n - Double file extensions, like
    a file named \u201Cinvoice.pdf.exe\u201D where the true file type is hidden behind
    a misleading name.  \n\nIf an attachment is present and unexpected, do not open
    it directly. Instead, submit it to a secure analysis environment or consult your
    security team if applicable.\n\n>>>  Understanding Phishing - Module #2  <<<\n\nPhishing
    is a deceptive practice used by attackers to trick individuals into giving up
    sensitive information. Rather than breaking into systems through technical means,
    phishing targets human judgment.\n\nMessages are crafted to look like they come
    from legitimate sources such as banks, employers, or well known online services.
    The intent is to create a sense of familiarity and trust so the recipient lowers
    their guard.\n\nPhishing is a form of social engineering; the attacker is not
    relying on sophisticated code as much as they are relying on convincing communication.
    This makes phishing both accessible to attackers and broadly effective.\n\n***
    The Structure of a Phishing Attempt ***\n\nA phishing message is rarely random.
    It is typically designed with a clear sequence in mind. First, the attacker establishes
    credibility by imitating a trusted sender. This could be done through logos,
    email formatting, or even spoofed addresses that look nearly identical to legitimate
    ones.\n\nOnce that initial trust is established, the message introduces a problem
    or opportunity. Often, it claims that an account has been compromised, a payment
    has failed, or immediate verification is required. The purpose is to provoke
    a quick emotional reaction before careful thinking can take place.\n\nFinally,
    the message pushes the recipient toward a specific action. This is usually clicking
    a link or opening an attachment. The link may lead to a convincing but fake website
    designed to capture login credentials, while attachments may install malicious
    software in the background.\n\n*** Why Phishing Is Effective ***\n\nPhishing
    works because it exploits predictable human behavior. People tend to respond
    quickly to perceived threats, especially when those threats involve money, security,
    or authority figures. When a message appears urgent, many individuals act before
    verifying its authenticity.\n\nAnother factor is routine. Digital communication
    is constant, and people are accustomed to clicking links and responding to notifications
    without much scrutiny. Attackers take advantage of this habit by blending malicious
    messages into the normal flow of emails and alerts.\n\nTrust also plays a major
    role. When a message appears to come from a recognizable brand or institution,
    recipients are more likely to assume it is legitimate. Even small visual cues,
    such as familiar logos or formatting, can reinforce this assumption.\n\n*** Recognizing
    Subtle Warning Signs ***\n\nAlthough phishing messages can appear convincing,
    they often contain small inconsistencies. It\u2019s important to slow down and
    examine messages more carefully. For example, a link might display one address
    but redirect to another when clicked.\n\nSimilarly, the tone of the message may
    feel slightly off, such as being overly urgent or unusually generic. Another
    common sign is a mismatch between the situation described and reality.\n\nA message
    might claim there is a problem with an account that the recipient does not even
    use, or it may request information that legitimate organizations typically do
    not ask for through email. These clues are easy to miss when acting quickly,
    which is why attackers rely so heavily on urgency.\n\n*** The Broader Impact
    of Phishing ***\n\nPhishing is not just an inconvenience. Its consequences can
    extend beyond a single compromised account. Once attackers obtain login credentials,
    they may access financial systems, steal personal data, or use the account to
    send further phishing messages to others.\n\nIn organizational settings, a single
    successful phishing attempt can lead to larger security breaches. This makes
    phishing one of the most common entry points for more serious cyberattacks.\n\n***
    Building Safer Habits ***\n\nUltimately, preventing phishing is less about technical
    expertise and more about consistent habits. Taking a moment to question unexpected
    messages can significantly reduce risk. Verifying requests through official channels
    rather than responding directly to a message is a simple but effective safeguard.\n\nOver
    time, developing a cautious mindset becomes the strongest defense. Phishing depends
    on quick, unexamined reactions. By slowing down and applying basic scrutiny,
    individuals can disrupt the entire attack.\n\n>>>  Scam Identification Review
    - Module #3  <<<\n\nScam emails are designed to create confusion, urgency, or
    excitement so people act before thinking carefully. While no single warning sign
    guarantees that an email is fraudulent, recognizing common patterns can help
    you avoid scams and protect your personal information.\n\n*** Start by Checking
    the Sender ***\n\nThe displayed sender name can be misleading. Scammers can make
    an email appear to come from a trusted company, organization, or person even
    when it does not. Instead of trusting the visible name alone:\n\n - Check the
    actual email address behind the sender name  \n - Be cautious if the address
    comes from a free email service or an unrelated domain  \n - Remember that even
    realistic-looking addresses can be faked  \n\nA legitimate business typically
    uses an official domain connected to its organization.\n\n*** Inspect Links Before
    Clicking ***\n\nMany scam emails attempt to direct you to fake websites designed
    to steal passwords or financial information. Before clicking any link:\n\n -
    Hover over it with your mouse to preview the destination  \n - On mobile devices,
    press and hold the link to reveal the URL  \n - Confirm the web address matches
    the official company website  \n\nScammers often disguise malicious links by
    making the visible text look legitimate while the actual destination leads elsewhere.\n\n***
    Be Careful with Phone Numbers ***\n\nSome scams try to move the conversation
    from email to phone. If an email urges you to call support:\n\n - Verify the
    phone number independently through the company\u2019s official website  \n -
    Search the number online to see whether others have reported it as fraudulent 
    \n\nEven if other parts of the email seem genuine, the phone number may still
    be fake.\n\n*** Watch for Generic Greetings ***\n\nFraudulent emails frequently
    use vague greetings such as:\n\n - \u201CDear Customer\u201D  \n - \u201CAccount
    Holder\u201D  \n - Your email username instead of your real name  \n\nOrganizations
    you already do business with usually know your name and often personalize important
    communications.\n\n*** Look for Poor Writing and Unusual Language ***\n\nScam
    emails often contain:\n\n - Grammar mistakes  \n - Strange phrasing  \n - Unusual
    formatting  \n - Inconsistent tone or wording  \n\nProfessional organizations
    generally review customer communications carefully. However, polished writing
    alone does not guarantee legitimacy, since some scams are highly sophisticated.\n\n***
    Notice Unprofessional Design ***\n\nPoor-quality graphics and awkward formatting
    can also be warning signs. Examples include:\n\n - Blurry or distorted logos 
    \n - Odd spacing or alignment  \n - Unusual colors or fonts  \n - Layouts that
    look inconsistent with official communications  \n\nComparing suspicious emails
    with genuine messages from the same organization can help reveal differences.\n\n***
    Be Suspicious of Urgency ***\n\nScammers frequently try to create panic or pressure
    by claiming:\n\n - Your account is suspended  \n - Unauthorized activity was
    detected  \n - Immediate action is required  \n - A payment deadline is approaching 
    \n\nUrgency is used to discourage careful thinking. Legitimate organizations
    rarely demand instant action through threatening email messages alone.\n\n***
    Be Wary of Unexpected Rewards or Good News ***\n\nSome scams promise:\n\n - Refunds 
    \n - Prize winnings  \n - Free money  \n - Exclusive offers  \n\nThese messages
    often attempt to collect personal information, payment details, or login credentials.
    Unexpected rewards should always be treated cautiously.\n\n*** Recognize Common
    Scam Themes ***\n\nMany scam emails follow familiar patterns, including:\n\n-
    Fake invoices or receipts  \n - Delivery problems with packages  \n - Toll or
    tax payment requests  \n - Job offers  \n - Password expiration notices  \n-
    Security alerts about suspicious account activity  \n - Claims that your device
    is infected with malware  \n\nThese messages succeed because they imitate situations
    people commonly encounter in daily life.\n\n*** Remember That Some Details May
    Be Real ***\n\nScammers often mix legitimate-looking information with fraudulent
    content. For example:\n\n - A real company name may appear alongside a fake phone
    number  \n - A legitimate-looking link may be included to build trust before
    directing you elsewhere  \n - Real-world events or common services may be referenced
    to make the message feel believable  \n\nBecause of this, a few \u201Ccorrect\u201D
    details do not prove an email is safe.\n\n*** What to Do If You Are Unsure ***\n\nIf
    a suspicious email references a real company or service you use:\n\n - Do not
    click links in the email  \n - Do not call numbers provided in the message  \n-
    Do not reply directly  \n\nInstead:\n\n - Visit the company\u2019s official website
    manually  \n - Log into your account through the official site  \n - Contact
    customer support using verified contact information  \n\nIf the issue is genuine,
    you will usually see evidence of it through your actual account or additional
    official communication channels.\n\n*** Stay Vigilant ***\n\nNo one is immune
    to scams. Even careful and experienced users can be caught off guard. The best
    protection is to:\n\n - Stay cautious with unexpected emails  \n - Slow down
    before reacting emotionally  \n - Verify information independently  \n - Keep
    informed about common scam tactics  \n\nRecognizing patterns and maintaining
    healthy skepticism can greatly reduce the risk of falling victim to fraudulent
    emails."
